.TE
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
The virtual page ( \fBvirpage\fP) element is the smallest,
directly addressable unit in a document\&. It corresponds to a topic\&. Ideally,
documents presented on-line (and perhaps even on paper) should be organized
into small topics that are complete unto themselves\&. This allows readers to
find and access the desired information\&.
.PP
A virtual page contains all information necessary to establish a formatting
context\&. Virtual pages may be displayed and understood when removed from
the context of the document as long as the table of semantics and styles
( \fBtoss\fP) element is available for formatting information\&.
.PP
A virtual page may have zero or more \fBhead\fP elements
that provide title information and may also be used in display decoration,
such as a title bar\&. The first \fBhead\fP of a virtual page is
intended to be displayed in a table of contents for the document\&.
.PP
Following the \fBhead\fP elements is an optional system
notation block ( \fBsnb\fP)\&. The system notation block, which
provides access to objects external to the document, is covered later in this
document\&.
.PP
Finally, a virtual page may contain any combination of \fBblock\fP or \fBform\fP elements, including none\&.
.PP
The attributes of \fBvirpage\fP are:
.TS
tab();
lw(0.611111i) lw(0.836257i) lw(0.836257i) lw(3.216374i).
\fIid\fPIDRequiredT{
The identifier of the virtual page\&. The \fIid\fP attribute  must be a valid SGML identifier and must be  unique
within the document\&. To display a virtual  page, hyperlink to this \fIid\fP\&.
T}
\fIlevel\fPNUMBERRequiredT{
The hierarchical level of the information
contained in the element\&. The \fIlevel\fP attribute
makes  explicit information that is implicit in typical  SGML conforming documents\&.
An SDL conforming document may be considered to have  been flattened to allow
direct access of inferior  topics\&. For example, if the source DTD specified
divisions such as \fBchapter\fP, \fBd1\fP, \fBd2\fP, these would all  appear in the SDL version of the document as
virtual pages but with levels of \fB1\fP, \fB2\fP
and \fB3\fP, respectively\&.
T}
\fIversion\fPCDATAOptionalT{
The version of this element\&. By default,
the version of the \fBvirpage\fP is the same as the version of
 the document (\fBsdldoc\fP)\&.
T}
\fIlanguage\fPCDATAOptionalT{
The language in which this element is written\&.
This attribute may be overridden individually within the \fBform\fP
and \fBblock\fP elements contained in the virtual page\&.
T}
\fIcharset\fPCDATAOptionalT{
The default character set of the document\&.
This attribute may be overridden individually within  the \fBform\fP
and \fBblock\fP elements contained in the virtual page\&.
T}
\fIdoc-id\fPCDATARequiredT{
The document identifier of the document to
 which this element belongs\&.
T}
\fIssi\fPCDATAOptionalT{
A source semantic identifier\&. This identifier
is  chosen by the author of a higher level DTD or  other source to SDL translator\&.
It may either  reflect the meaning of the markup in the original  document
or may reflect the actual generic identifier in the original document\&. The
source semantic identifier may be used to  assist in semantic searches of
the SDL conforming document by preserving the original intent of  the markup\&.
When the original markup was conforming to a domain specific DTD, the \fIssi\fP may be  used to enable structured searches of the SDL  conforming
document by preserving the original  generic identifiers\&.
T}
.TE
.PP
The \fIlevel\fP and \fIssi\fP
attributes of the virtual page are used to look up formatting and semantic
information in the table of semantics and styles ( \fBtoss\fP)
element covered later in this document\&.
